	A quick review of some concepts we covered during lecture 26:
    \vspace{5mm}
    \[
        E_{i} = E_{f}
    \] 
    \[
    E_{i} + W = E_{f}
    \]
    \begin{table}[h!]
            \begin{center}
                    \caption{Table of Force-to-Work Conversions}
                    \begin{tabular}{l|c r} 
                    \textbf{Force} & \textbf{1-D} & \textbf{N-D} \\
                    \hline
                    \emph{Const} & $F\Delta(x)$ & $\vec{F}\vec{\Delta(x)}$ \\
                    \emph{Variable} & $\int_{x_{i}}^{x_{f}} Fdx$ & $\int_{x_{i}}^{x_{f}} \vec{F}\vec{dx}$ \\
                    \end{tabular}
            \end{center}
    \end{table}
    \[
            \vec{a}.\vec{b} = abcos\theta
    \] 
    \[
    = a_{x}b_{x}+a_{y}b_{y}+a_{z}+b_{z}
    \] 
    \[ 
            F_{U} = -\frac{dU}{dx}
    \] 
    \par\noindent\rule{\textwidth}{0.2pt}
    \vspace{3mm}
    \textbf{Work, Friction and Heat:} \\
    \vspace{2mm}
    Friction drains system energy into 'waste' heat, or unusable energy. \\
    \begin{enumerate}
    	\item $W_{heat} = E_{f} - E_{i}$, $W$ will always be negative.
        \item $E_{i} = E_{f} + \Delta(E)_{th}$ - Heat energy created by $F\Delta(x)$
    \end{enumerate}
    \par\noindent\rule{\textwidth}{0.2pt}
    \vspace{3mm}
    \textbf{Power:} rate of use of energy, measured in Watts: $W = 1 \frac{J}{s}$. \\
    \[
    P = \frac{dE}{dt} = \frac{\Delta(E)}{\Delta(t)}
    \] 
    \[
    P = F*U
    \]
    or
    \[
    P = \vec{F}\vec{V} = FVcos\theta
    \] 
